through this?

14:04.310 --> 14:12.318 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
SANGER: One point is every state has a different
system and different levels of cyber security.

14:12.418 --> 14:18.925 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
And if there was one big lesson from the 2016
election, apart from the issues between the

14:19.025 --> 14:24.097 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
candidates, is that we are vulnerable to a
foreign power to come in and attempting to

14:24.197 --> 14:27.900 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
influence the election and that s of course
what the intelligence agencies were saying

14:28.000 --> 14:36.175 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
about the hacks of the DNC and John Podesta,
the chairman of the Clinton campaign s e-mails.

14:36.275 --> 14:44.217 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
If that s the case, we have to all up our
game for sanctity of the election system.

14:44.317 --> 14:49.722 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
I think if states understand, that they are
going to be required to go back and look at

14:49.822 --> 14:57.396 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
the paper ballots either on a sample or full
basis, they will probably invest more in their

14:57.497 --> 15:03.436 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
cyber security if they believe that there
is a chance that there could be hacking, they

15:03.536 --> 15:05.238 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
need a better system.

15:05.338 --> 15:10.977 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
In this particular case, when the issue is
this narrow, if they don t go back and do

15:11.077 --> 15:16.549 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
it, there will be conspiracy theories between
now and 30 years from now saying the 2016

15:16.649 --> 15:22.789 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
election, there was something suspect there.
So if they pass up this chance, they will

15:22.889 --> 15:28.594 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
open up to the conspiracy theories having
their case even if their case is unfounded.

15:28.694 --> 15:34.467 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
YANG: So, is it do it to prove that nothing
happened that there was no hacking?

15:34.567 --> 15:40.940 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
SANGER: I think it s do it to be sure there
was no hacking and do it to make sure states

15:41.040 --> 15:46.245 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
recognize if they don t have the best cyber
security around which includes understanding

15:46.345 --> 15:51.050 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
what sort of malware can come into the systems
and investing in the front end, they probably

15:51.150 --> 15:55.488 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
will have to pay a lot more money at the back
end if elections close.

15:55.588 --> 16:01.160 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Remember, the way the states are doing this
right now, you only do a recount if the two

16:01.260 --> 16:10.136 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
people running are within half a percent or
less of each other. For a half of an election,

16:10.236 --> 16:16.042 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
that wouldn t make sense because any sophisticated
hacker is going to know that the state s cutoff

16:16.142 --> 16:22.315 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
is half of one percent and make sure the margin
is slightly larger than that to avoid an automatic

16:22.415 --> 16:27.920 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
recount. So you ve got to stay one thought
out ahead of some very sophisticated hackers.

16:28.020 --> 16:36.729 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
YANG: David Sanger of the New York Times.
Thanks for joining us.

16:36.829 --> 16:40.032 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
SANGER: Thank you.

16:40.132 --> 16:45.204 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
YANG: The president of Colombia signed a new
peace deal with FARC rebels this morning,

16:45.304 --> 16:51.043 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
about six weeks after voters narrowly rejected
an earlier agreement. Days after that vote,

16:51.143 --> 16:55.748 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
president Juan Manuel Santos received the
Nobel peace prize for his efforts to end that

16:55.848 --> 17:01.187 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
five-decade OLD war. For more, I m joined
from Bogota by special correspondent Nadja

17:01.287 --> 17:05.791 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Drost. Nadja, how significant were the changes
that were made after the referendum?

17:05.892 --> 17:09.996 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
NADJA DROST, PBS CORRESPONDENT: Well, John,
the government and the FARC said they incorporated

17:10.096 --> 17:17.069 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
many if not most to have the changes that
no campaigners and opponents of the PCL had

17:17.169 --> 17:18.804 align:left position:87.5%,start line:93.33% size:12.5%
voiced. The current PCL. That was just

17:18.905 --> 17:20.640 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
[0: 20: 00. 3]

17:20.740 --> 17:26.078 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
signed has included over 50 changes, among
them the FARC has promised that they will

17:26.178 --> 17:32.251 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
reveal all information related to narco trafficking
and drug trafficking routes to help out law

17:32.351 --> 17:38.224 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
enforcement. But could it say that many of
the changes in this new deal don t go far

17:38.324 --> 17:42.161 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
enough in punishing the FARC in serious human
rights abuses.

17:42.261 --> 17:47.667 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
For example, one to have the main arguments
is FARC leaders should not be able to run

17:47.767 --> 17:53.339 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
for political office while still serving alternative
sentence force atrocities committed.

17:53.439 --> 17:59.478 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
YANG: Why was the government insistent on
getting it renegotiated and signed quickly?

17:59.578 --> 18:05.084 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
DROST: There is a real sense of urgency here
to get this peace process back on track because

18:05.184 --> 18:12.825 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
simple referendum and the PCL failed on October
2nd. We have about 7,000 FARC fighters spread

18:12.925 --> 18:18.998 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
out across the country in judicial limbo and
their demobilization has been paralyzed. While

18:19.098 --> 18:24.670 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
there is a bilateral seize fire in place,
it s fragility was demonstrated. Earlier this

18:24.770 --> 18:35.348 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
month two FARC guerillas were killed. This
weekend at least three random activists and

18:35.448 --> 18:40.820 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
leaders in a social movement assassinated
and another one killed this morning.

18:40.920 --> 18:47.727 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
YANG: What are the next steps? What are the
challenges in implementing this peace deal?

18:47.827 --> 18:53.265 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
DROST: President Santos decided not to put
this new peace deal to a popular vote as he

18:53.366 --> 18:59.872 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
did last time and it failed. Instead, he is
sending it immediately to congress for approval.

18:59.972 --> 19:06.312 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
While we don t yet know if the implementation
of the deal will get fast tracked into congress

19:06.412 --> 19:09.715 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
or dragged out in debates.

19:09.815 --> 19:16.555 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
We know the opponents to this deal in congress
lead by former president Alavaro Uribe have

19:16.655 --> 19:22.361 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
vowed to oppose the deal, but how much they ll
actually will be able to do in congress considering

19:22.461 --> 19:29.301 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
they re a minority is it s not looking very
hopeful for them to actually help any legislative

19:29.402 --> 19:31.137 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
changes.

19:31.237 --> 19:34.573 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
YANG: Nadja, this has been a bit of a roller
coaster ride, the peace agreement reached,

19:34.673 --> 19:39.945 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
rejected by the referendum, renegotiated and
signed. What s the mood of the public now?

19:40.046 --> 19:48.454 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
DROST: We re here in Bogota s main square,
the Plaza Bolivar. There is definitely a sense

19:48.554 --> 19:54.994 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
