cuisine can be found on nearly every street
corner, one entrepreneur is relying on refugees

37:07.292 --> 37:10.095 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
to bring their home cooking to New York City
foodies.

37:10.195 --> 37:13.498 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
William Brangham is back with a visit to a
Long Island kitchen,

37:13.598 --> 37:15.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
(BEGIN VIDEOTAPE)

37:15.467 --> 37:17.168 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM, PBS NEWSHOUR CORRESPONDENT:
It s business as usual inside the kitchen

37:17.268 --> 37:22.340 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
of Eat Offbeat -- a New York City catering
company. Recipes, prepared with precision

37:22.440 --> 37:28.480 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
slicing and dicing, are cooked to perfection.
But the chefs here all have one thing in common:

37:28.580 --> 37:34.219 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
they re refugees, and none of them, until
recently, had any formal culinary training

37:34.319 --> 37:38.623 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
MANAL KAHI, FOUNDER EAT OFFBEAT: Today, we
have chefs from Syria, Iraq, Nepal, Eritrea,

37:38.723 --> 37:43.928 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
the Ivory Coast, Guinea-Conakry. They re all
working each on their own dish and we have

37:44.028 --> 37:45.830 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
a few deliveries happening this afternoon.

37:45.930 --> 37:50.902 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
BRANGHAM: Manal Kahi created Eat Offbeat with
her brother Wissam last year. The idea came

37:51.002 --> 37:57.242 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
to them a few years before, after Kahi kept
trying different brands of American made hummus

37:57.342 --> 37:59.444 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
and nothing measured up to her grandmother s
recipe.

37:59.544 --> 38:05.717 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
KAHI: I had recently moved to the U.S. from
Lebanon and I kind of missed my home. In the

38:05.817 --> 38:11.055 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
midst of the refugee crisis back in Lebanon,
our grandmother happens to be from Aleppo,

38:11.156 --> 38:16.294 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
from Syria, originally. It was relatively
natural for us to say if you want someone

38:16.394 --> 38:21.866 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
as talented as our grandmother to make hummus
for New Yorkers, maybe we should see the refugees

38:21.966 --> 38:25.069 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
coming from Syria. We probably would findsomeone who s just like her.

38:25.170 --> 38:30.175 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
BRANGHAM: That idea soon grew beyond just
Syrians -- Kahi believed that talented home

38:30.275 --> 38:35.380 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
cooks from across the globe could offer New
Yorkers unique flavors, prepared in traditional

38:35.480 --> 38:37.282 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
ways.

38:37.382 --> 38:42.720 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
KAHI: Cuisines like Iraqi food, Syrian, Nepali,
Eritrean, it s not really cuisines that you

38:42.820 --> 38:47.025 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
can find around every corner even here in
New York, as cosmopolitan as it can be. When

38:47.125 --> 38:51.496 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
we say authentic, it s not necessarily the
way it s made in that country or it s been

38:51.596 --> 38:55.200 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
made in that country hundred years ago. It s
the way they make it at home, the way they

38:55.300 --> 38:58.937 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
eat it with their families. That s the way
we re selling it.

38:59.037 --> 39:02.974 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
BRANGHAM: Eat Offbeat partners with the International
Rescue Committee to find their chefs, and

39:03.074 --> 39:08.313 align:left position:62.5%,start line:93.33% size:37.5%
twelve of them are now employed with the company.

39:08.413 --> 39:12.150 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Because it s their first time working in a
professional kitchen, they need a bit of training,

39:12.250 --> 39:17.555 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
and so, the culinary process is overseen by
head chef Juan Suarez De Lezo. He s worked

39:17.655 --> 39:20.792 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
at some of the top restaurants in both Spain
and the U.S.

39:20.892 --> 39:23.928 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
JUAN SUAREZ DE LEZO, HEAD CHEF: I m teaching
them how to move in a professional kitchen,

39:24.028 --> 39:29.567 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
how to work, how to organize, how to balance
flavors, because at the end, they ve been

39:29.667 --> 39:34.505 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
cooking always for their families which is
amazing, but in this case, now they re cooking

39:34.606 --> 39:39.310 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
for New Yorkers. So, they need to adapt thoseflavors in somehow for the city.

39:39.410 --> 39:45.083 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
BRANGHAM: For Rachana Rimal, a Nepalese chef,
she s been preparing a dish that is generally

39:45.183 --> 39:47.352 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
served at special occasions in her country.

39:47.452 --> 39:50.855 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
RACHANA RIMAL, CHIEF, EAT OFFBEAT: This isa chicken ball, actually.

39:50.955 --> 39:52.690 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
BRANGHAM: Like a meatball?

39:52.790 --> 39:55.927 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
RIMAL: Like a meatball but I put a lot of
spices on it, like onions and my ingredients

39:56.027 --> 39:59.631 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
here, culmi, mustard. I put everything here.

39:59.731 --> 40:07.272 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
BRANGHAM: Rimal s daughter Satakshi came to
the U.S. with her a few years ago when they

40:07.372 --> 40:13.144 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
fled Nepal as a family. She works as the kitchen
manager for Eat Offbeat. With a meticulous

40:13.244 --> 40:18.616 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
eye, she oversees deliveries, portion sizes,
and, for the first time in her life, keeping

40:18.716 --> 40:20.485 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
her own mom in line.

40:20.585 --> 40:23.421 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
SATAKSHI RIMAL, KITCHEN MANAGER, EAT OFFBEAT:
I get to boss her around here and she gets

40:23.521 --> 40:27.892 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
to boss me around at home. So, I think weeven each other out pretty well.

40:27.992 --> 40:32.263 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
BRANGHAM: Larry Younck is a senior refugee
resettlement officer for the United Nations

40:32.363 --> 40:37.101 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
in Washington, D.C. Younck says cooking is
often a perfect job for refugees when they

40:37.201 --> 40:38.970 align:left position:87.5%,start line:93.33% size:12.5%
first arrive to the United States.

40:39.070 --> 40:40.805 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
LARRY YOUNCK, SENIOR REFUGEE RESETTLEMENT
OFFICER, UNITED NATIONS: Refugees are expected

40:40.905 --> 40:44.575 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
to be self-supporting very quickly, a few
months after arriving here, and to find jobs

40:44.676 --> 40:49.380 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
in the U.S. and that can be a challenge when
you don t speak English or you speak limited

40:49.480 --> 40:55.353 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
English and your job skills maybe are hard
to transfer from your home country. But when

40:55.453 --> 41:01.292 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
it comes to food, food communicates regardless
of whether you can speak English or not.

41:01.392 --> 41:05.663 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
BRANGHAM: Younck also believes more companies
should follow Eat Offbeat s lead when it comes

41:05.763 --> 41:07.665 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to hiring refugees.

41:07.765 --> 41:12.937 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
YOUNCK: What we see is refugees in general
in a lot of walks of life are much more entrepreneurial

41:13.037 --> 41:19.510 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
than typically Americans are because, again,
they ve taken risks. They know what it is

41:19.610 --> 41:22.680 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
to try something and maybe you succeed and
maybe you don t.

41:22.780 --> 41:27.652 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
BRANGHAM: But Manal Kahi wants her company
to go further, not just to offer jobs, but

41:27.752 --> 41:31.489 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
to help change the perception of refugees
as just being vulnerable, needy people.

41:31.589 --> 41:36.828 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
KAHI: That s exactly what they re trying to
prove wrong. In our opinion, refugees are

41:36.928 --> 41:42.800 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
very skilled. They bring with them a lot of
skills, a lot of talent, a lot of heritage

41:42.900 --> 41:47.972 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
that they can share with their host communities.
And given the right opportunity, the right

41:48.072 --> 41:52.276 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
space, they have a lot to contribute for the
local economy, and for the local communities.

41:52.377 --> 41:57.782 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
BRANGHAM: And for employees like Satakshi
Rimal, she says the kitchen has become a place

41:57.882 --> 42:00.485 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
where chefs do much more than simply cook.

42:00.585 --> 42:06.591 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
RIMAL: The best I could describe is it s a
second home to everybody. It s like a bunch

42:06.691 --> 42:11.529 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
of aunts coming in, cooking at a common kitchen.
And, you know, it s like joint family so you

42:11.629 --> 42:15.133 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
have everything that happens in a household.
There s screaming, there s, "hey, don t put

42:15.233 --> 42:19.137 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
too much of this. Don t put so much of it."Even if that s not their dish.

42:19.237 --> 42:23.408 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
BRANGHAM: Eat Offbeat mainly caters to large
groups, but is hoping to expand into a delivery

42:23.508 --> 42:29.280 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
service in the coming months. And as for the
hummus -- Kahi says her company s recipe would

42:29.380 --> 42:30.782 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
make grandma proud.

42:30.882 --> 42:32.784 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Mmm, that is great.

42:32.884 --> 42:37.121 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
For the "PBS NewsHour", I m William Brangham
in New York.

42:37.221 --> 42:38.923 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
