doctor to primarily see people with diabetes,

01:01:11.935 --> 01:01:12.802 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
heart disease and cancer, and I was shocked
by the number of patients who came under my

01:01:12.903 --> 01:01:14.604 align:left position:87.5%,start line:93.33% size:12.5%
care who actually had substance abuse.

01:01:14.704 --> 01:01:15.272 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
BRANGHAM: You were seeing this in private
practice before being tapped to be in the

01:01:15.372 --> 01:01:17.073 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
federal government?

01:01:17.173 --> 01:01:17.774 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
MURTHY: Yes, I have always seen this -- we
even -- starting in medical school itself

01:01:17.874 --> 01:01:18.341 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and then on throughout

01:01:18.441 --> 01:01:20.210 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
[0: 25: 00. 1]

01:01:20.310 --> 01:01:21.545 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
my medical career, the experience was not
unique to me but many of my clinician colleagues

01:01:21.645 --> 01:01:23.346 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
were seeing the same thing and they were really
surprised.

01:01:23.446 --> 01:01:25.148 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
When I became surgeon general and had the
privilege of travelling around the country

01:01:25.248 --> 01:01:27.050 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
and hearing people s stories firsthand, I
found that every community was touched in

01:01:27.150 --> 01:01:28.852 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
some way by substance abuse disorders. I went
to a small fishing village in Alaska called

01:01:28.952 --> 01:01:30.787 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Napaskiak which is accessible only by boat
and no roads to go there and even in this

01:01:30.887 --> 01:01:32.589 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
small village of less than 500 people, the
small little building where they kept medications

01:01:32.689 --> 01:01:34.558 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
had been broken into multiple times by people
seeking out prescription painkillers.

01:01:34.658 --> 01:01:36.393 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
BRANGHAM: You say in this report that we as
a nation need to think differently about addiction

01:01:36.493 --> 01:01:37.294 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
and to look at substance abuse and addiction
differently. How do we look at it now and

01:01:37.394 --> 01:01:39.129 align:left position:87.5%,start line:93.33% size:12.5%
what would you like to see change?

01:01:39.229 --> 01:01:41.064 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
MURTHY: Unfortunately, for too many people,
addiction is a disease of choice, they see

01:01:41.164 --> 01:01:42.899 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
as a character flaw as evidence of moral failing,
but what we know they are clearly from the

01:01:42.999 --> 01:01:43.400 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
science, is that addiction is actually none
of those things it s a chronic disease of

01:01:43.500 --> 01:01:45.201 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the brain.

01:01:45.302 --> 01:01:47.103 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
We have good scientific studies that tell
us that addiction impacts the circuits in

01:01:47.203 --> 01:01:48.972 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
your brain and in specific parts of the brain
that affect impulse control, decision making

01:01:49.072 --> 01:01:50.907 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
and your stress and reward response. When
we understand that, we start to have a better

01:01:51.007 --> 01:01:51.975 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
sense of why it is so easy for people to relapse
with substance abuse disorders and why people

01:01:52.075 --> 01:01:53.977 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
experience withdrawal symptoms and cravings.

01:01:54.077 --> 01:01:54.811 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
BRANGHAM: Can you explain -- that number really
jumps, 440 billion dollars in costs from substance

01:01:54.911 --> 01:01:56.680 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
abuse. How do the costs add up?

01:01:56.780 --> 01:01:58.548 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
MURTHY: These costs come from several streams.
One is from direct healthcare costs. Also

01:01:58.648 --> 01:02:00.483 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
losses in workplace productivity as well as
criminal justice system costs. The good news

01:02:00.584 --> 01:02:01.451 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
is we have evidence-based treatment and prevention
strategies at work. The problem is they re

01:02:01.551 --> 01:02:03.253 align:left position:87.5%,start line:93.33% size:12.5%
just not getting it to enough people.

01:02:03.353 --> 01:02:04.721 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
BRANGHAM: Why is that? You report details
quite a bit of these things that you argue

01:02:04.821 --> 01:02:06.623 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
absolutely are proven to work but aren t being
used, why is that?

01:02:06.723 --> 01:02:08.525 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
MURTHY: It s really striking and it s especially
striking when you recognize it. Not only do

01:02:08.625 --> 01:02:10.460 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
we have a humanitarian reason to get treatments
to people but we know that for every dollar

01:02:10.560 --> 01:02:12.462 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
that we invest in treatment we save four dollars
in healthcare costs, seven dollars in criminal

01:02:12.562 --> 01:02:13.296 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
justice system costs. We have prevention programs
that are proven, that can save up to 64 dollars

01:02:13.396 --> 01:02:15.231 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
for every one dollar invested.

01:02:15.332 --> 01:02:17.133 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
A part of the reason that people haven t gotten
these treatments is that, as a country, number

01:02:17.233 --> 01:02:18.969 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
one, we haven t invested enough in expansion
of treatment programs. Number two, we haven t

01:02:19.069 --> 01:02:20.804 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
trained our clinicians widely enough in how
to recognize, diagnose and treat substance

01:02:20.904 --> 01:02:22.405 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
abuse disorders and, third, there is this
ongoing, unfortunate stigma around substance

01:02:22.505 --> 01:02:24.207 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
abuse disorders that prevents people fromseeking help in the first place.

01:02:24.307 --> 01:02:25.875 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
BRANGHAM: On the prevention side, what is
it that works? What is it that we know can

01:02:25.976 --> 01:02:27.744 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
be done to help people to stop these substanceabuse problems from developing?

01:02:27.844 --> 01:02:29.546 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
MURTHY: Well, the good news is that, there
are prevention programs that don t just target

01:02:29.646 --> 01:02:31.448 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
one particular kind of substance but they
can be effective reducing rates of use of

01:02:31.548 --> 01:02:33.316 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
alcohol, tobacco as well as elicit substances
particularly by our youth and these programs

01:02:33.416 --> 01:02:35.185 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
are varied but some of them are school-based
programs, one called the behavior game which

01:02:35.285 --> 01:02:36.987 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
trains young children in how to deal with
stress in a healthy way and how to understand

01:02:37.087 --> 01:02:38.888 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
some of these substances of misuse and understand
how to deal with them responsibly.

01:02:38.989 --> 01:02:40.757 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
There are also community-based programs that
focus on education and on dealing with stress

01:02:40.857 --> 01:02:42.626 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
in a healthy way. And this is a key point
which is, as I ve traveled around the country,

01:02:42.726 --> 01:02:44.461 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
I have found many times when people are using
substances or when they begin, they begin

01:02:44.561 --> 01:02:46.329 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
trying to medicate some type of pain they re
experiencing. It may not be physical pain.

01:02:46.429 --> 01:02:48.265 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
It may be emotional pain or stress they re
experiencing. If we can help equip young people

01:02:48.365 --> 01:02:49.032 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
in particular with healthy ways of dealing
with stress we can go a long way toward preventing

01:02:49.132 --> 01:02:50.967 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
substance abuse disorders.

01:02:51.067 --> 01:02:52.769 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
BRANGHAM: There are many people in the treatment
and the substance abuse world who are so cheered

01:02:52.869 --> 01:02:54.671 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
