01:04:17.253 --> 01:04:17.854 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SOLMAN: But they are wealthy.

01:04:17.954 --> 01:04:19.723 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
FREEDMAN: Definitely.

01:04:19.823 --> 01:04:20.390 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
SOLMAN: The new money wanted food that was
fancy French, with new world twists. Delmonico s

01:04:20.490 --> 01:04:21.925 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
steak, a rib-eye --

01:04:22.025 --> 01:04:22.826 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
FREEDMAN: They invented Lobster Newburg. They
invented Baked Alaska.

01:04:22.926 --> 01:04:24.427 align:left position:87.5%,start line:93.33% size:12.5%
SOLMAN: They even invented brunch.

01:04:24.527 --> 01:04:25.328 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
TV HOST: Delmonico s is credited with creatingthis brunch dish -- Erin.

01:04:25.428 --> 01:04:25.895 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
&nbsp;
CONTESTANT: What is Eggs Benedict?

01:04:25.995 --> 01:04:27.497 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
TV HOST: Good.

01:04:27.597 --> 01:04:29.165 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
SOLMAN: This was the place to meet and eat,well into the 20th century.

01:04:29.265 --> 01:04:30.734 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
UNIDENTIFIED MALE: We re going to Delmonico sfor supper, won t you join us?

01:04:30.834 --> 01:04:31.701 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
UNIDENTIFIED MALE: What will it be tonight,Delmonico s or the Plaza?

01:04:31.801 --> 01:04:33.503 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
&nbsp;
UNIDENTIFIED MALE: Lunch at Delmonico s!

01:04:33.603 --> 01:04:34.037 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
FREEDMAN: And men and women would show up
together at night, but at lunch, it would

01:04:34.137 --> 01:04:35.839 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
be men only.

01:04:35.939 --> 01:04:37.674 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
SOLMAN: Gender exclusivity, which, at the
turn of the 20th century, invited a second

01:04:37.774 --> 01:04:38.208 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
of freedman s top ten to enter the fray and
helped change America s expanding economy:

01:04:38.308 --> 01:04:40.009 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Schrafft s.

01:04:40.110 --> 01:04:40.844 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
I remember going to Schrafft s in the 50s
for the sundaes, I believe. The ice cream

01:04:40.944 --> 01:04:42.779 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
sundaes. That was a real treat.

01:04:42.879 --> 01:04:44.581 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
FREEDMAN: I too remember going there with
my grandmother. It s one of the first restaurants

01:04:44.681 --> 01:04:46.516 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
to cater to women, not just by providing a
safe atmosphere, but by providing the kind

01:04:46.616 --> 01:04:48.384 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
of food that women were thought to like to
eat -- light food followed by very rich desserts.

01:04:48.485 --> 01:04:49.085 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
SOLMAN: But now when Schrafft s starts in
1900, what does that say about what s happening

01:04:49.185 --> 01:04:50.920 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in the American economy?

01:04:51.020 --> 01:04:52.789 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
FREEDMAN: We see the rise of a middle middle
class of the sort that we know. They want

01:04:52.889 --> 01:04:53.723 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
a nice experience. They want food that is
relatively simple or not particularly French.

01:04:53.823 --> 01:04:55.592 align:left position:87.5%,start line:93.33% size:12.5%
SOLMAN: A democratized middle class.

01:04:55.692 --> 01:04:57.427 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
FREEDMAN: Yes, exactly. And so the restaurant
options are often for couples, you have to

01:04:57.527 --> 01:04:59.262 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
wait for Howard Johnson s and roadside restaurants
for children really to be featured.

01:04:59.362 --> 01:05:01.097 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
SOLMAN: Number three: Howard Johnson s, now
nearly extinct, with just one upstate New

01:05:01.197 --> 01:05:02.065 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
York outpost for fried clams and Frankforts,
down from a thousand such orange-and-blue

01:05:02.165 --> 01:05:03.867 align:left position:87.5%,start line:93.33% size:12.5%
emporia in its mid-20th-century heyday.

01:05:03.967 --> 01:05:05.602 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
FREEDMAN: In the 1920s, the American dream
was not to own a house, the American dream

01:05:05.702 --> 01:05:06.302 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
was to own a car and to drive with your family
around to look at the countryside.

01:05:06.402 --> 01:05:08.204 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
SOLMAN: Sunday drives.

01:05:08.304 --> 01:05:10.140 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
FREEDMAN: Sunday drives. Howard Deering Johnson
developed a restaurant concept that offered

01:05:10.240 --> 01:05:12.041 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
food particularly by the side of the new highways
that were opening up for leisure driving.

01:05:12.142 --> 01:05:12.742 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
SOLMAN: So the advent and success of Howard
Johnson s represents a further democratization

01:05:12.842 --> 01:05:14.577 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of the American economy?

01:05:14.677 --> 01:05:15.912 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
FREEDMAN: Yes, and it may be an early symbol
of the hollowing out of the middle level.

01:05:16.012 --> 01:05:17.781 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
SOLMAN: With HoJo s decline tracking growing
inequality.

01:05:17.881 --> 01:05:19.215 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
FREEDMAN: Because on the one hand you would
have very democratic places like McDonald s.

01:05:19.315 --> 01:05:21.117 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
And on the other hand you have more and more
fancy restaurants.

01:05:21.217 --> 01:05:22.419 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
SOLMAN: Hoity-toity boites like change agent
number four, Le Pavillon, where chef and owner

01:05:22.519 --> 01:05:24.254 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Henri Soule sat A-listers up front, to see
and be seen.

01:05:24.354 --> 01:05:25.221 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
FREEDMAN: So lots of other places like La
Caravelle, La Grenouille, all of them begin

01:05:25.321 --> 01:05:27.056 align:left position:87.5%,start line:93.33% size:12.5%
with Le and La, imitated this pattern.

01:05:27.157 --> 01:05:28.291 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
SOLMAN: Or number five, The Four Seasons,
birthplace of seasonal menus and the modern

01:05:28.391 --> 01:05:30.226 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
power lunch in an increasingly financialized
economy.

01:05:30.326 --> 01:05:30.894 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
FREEDMAN: When it started to have these power
lunches it was more media people. Advertising,

01:05:30.994 --> 01:05:31.795 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
TV, book publishing.

01:05:31.895 --> 01:05:33.663 align:left position:87.5%,start line:93.33% size:12.5%
SOLMAN: That s the 60s and 70s.

01:05:33.763 --> 01:05:35.465 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
FREEDMAN: 60s and 70s. I asked one of the
owners if that was still true, if there were

01:05:35.565 --> 01:05:36.933 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
still literary agents and authors, and he
looked at me pityingly. He looked at me as

01:05:37.033 --> 01:05:38.034 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
if I had asked to send a telegram or where
the nearest automat was.

01:05:38.134 --> 01:05:39.302 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
SOLMAN: Because it had become high end finance.

01:05:39.402 --> 01:05:40.937 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
FREEDMAN: It s finance and real estate. Serious
money.

01:05:41.037 --> 01:05:42.839 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
SOLMAN: There s one big apple restaurant togo: number six, Mamma Leone s.

01:05:42.939 --> 01:05:44.774 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
FREEDMAN: People say, well how can you have
Italian food in the United States represented

01:05:44.874 --> 01:05:46.576 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
by a place that was so mass market, so touristy.
That s part of the story of food in the United

01:05:46.676 --> 01:05:47.410 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
States. Mamma Leone s was a pioneer of the
spectacle restaurant. And it introduced a

01:05:47.510 --> 01:05:48.878 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
lot of people to Italian food.

01:05:48.978 --> 01:05:50.880 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
SOLMAN: Marking the true globalization of
the American economy.

01:05:50.980 --> 01:05:52.982 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
And that was also manifest on the West Coast.
Thus, number seven, The Mandarin in San Francisco,

01:05:53.082 --> 01:05:54.884 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
where in 1961 chef-owner Cecilia Chang introduced
people to Chinese food north and west of Cantonese.

01:05:54.984 --> 01:05:55.451 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
FREEDMAN: Not just one province of southern
China, as had been the case with Chinese food

01:05:55.552 --> 01:05:57.387 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
up to that time.

01:05:57.487 --> 01:05:59.189 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
SOLMAN: OK, we ve reached 1971 and Freedman s
restaurant number eight. America was now rich

01:05:59.289 --> 01:06:01.057 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
enough to start caring about something new
in its food -- how fresh it was; how safe.

01:06:01.157 --> 01:06:01.491 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Thus Chez Panisse, in Berkeley, California,
where chef-owner Alice Waters was the change

01:06:01.591 --> 01:06:03.393 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
agent...

01:06:03.493 --> 01:06:05.228 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
FREEDMAN: Changing the way many, many people
eat. It s influenced what public schools serve.

01:06:05.328 --> 01:06:06.629 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
It s influenced what Walmart and Target have
available in their produce sections. It s

01:06:06.729 --> 01:06:08.531 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
influenced restaurants pretty far down the
price food chain.

01:06:08.631 --> 01:06:09.966 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
SOLMAN: Number nine? Antoine s of New Orleans,
owned and run by the same family since 1840.

01:06:10.066 --> 01:06:11.868 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
An example of regional American cuisine: in
this case. Creole.

01:06:11.968 --> 01:06:12.702 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
CARTOON CHARACTER: You can t beat a good old
Back-bay Bayou Bunny Bordelais, a la Antoine.

01:06:12.802 --> 01:06:13.803 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
SOLMAN: America as melting pot.

01:06:13.903 --> 01:06:15.071 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
CARTOON CHARACTER: ZE Antoine of New Orleans?

01:06:15.171 --> 01:06:16.940 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
CARTOON CHARACTER: I don t mean Antoine of
Flatbush!

01:06:17.040 --> 01:06:17.974 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
FREEDMAN: Regional food is part of the heritage
of America and it s something that s being

01:06:18.074 --> 01:06:19.776 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
brought back, particularly Southern food.

01:06:19.876 --> 01:06:21.644 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
SOLMAN: Which brings us back to number 10,
Sylvia s in Harlem, where the Woods family

01:06:21.744 --> 01:06:22.445 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
carries on old traditions, and new ones, like
the timely Thanksgiving take-home package

01:06:22.545 --> 01:06:24.447 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
for an ever busier America.

01:06:24.547 --> 01:06:26.349 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
WOODS-BLACK: You ve got turkey, you have dressing,
you have collard greens, macaroni and cheese,

01:06:26.449 --> 01:06:28.184 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
cornbread, sweet potato pie, you have everything
that you need that in the end, you can take

01:06:28.284 --> 01:06:28.818 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
a little flour and just like, put it on your
face to make you look like a Thanksgiving

01:06:28.918 --> 01:06:30.687 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
dinner superstar.

01:06:30.787 --> 01:06:31.921 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
SOLMAN: Without all the effort. Time is money,
wrote Ben Franklin in 1748, which is a key

01:06:32.021 --> 01:06:33.590 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
reason Americans have been eating out, ever
since.

01:06:33.690 --> 01:06:34.157 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Reporting from New York, economics correspondentPaul Solman, thoroughly sated.

01:06:34.257 --> 01:06:36.025 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
&nbsp;
(END VIDEOTAPE)

01:06:36.125 --> 01:06:37.927 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
YANG: And now, a second helping of our food
theme. At a part of the country where ethnic

01:06:38.027 --> 01:06:39.162 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
cuisine can be found on nearly every street
corner, one entrepreneur is relying on refugees

01:06:39.262 --> 01:06:40.597 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
to bring their home cooking to New York City
foodies.

01:06:40.697 --> 01:06:41.231 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
William Brangham is back with a visit to a
Long Island kitchen,

01:06:41.331 --> 01:06:43.099 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
(BEGIN VIDEOTAPE)

01:06:43.199 --> 01:06:44.901 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM, PBS NEWSHOUR CORRESPONDENT:
It s business as usual inside the kitchen

01:06:45.001 --> 01:06:46.836 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
of Eat Offbeat -- a New York City catering
company. Recipes, prepared with precision

01:06:46.936 --> 01:06:48.638 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
slicing and dicing, are cooked to perfection.
But the chefs here all have one thing in common:

01:06:48.738 --> 01:06:50.473 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
they re refugees, and none of them, until
recently, had any formal culinary training

01:06:50.573 --> 01:06:52.308 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
MANAL KAHI, FOUNDER EAT OFFBEAT: Today, we
have chefs from Syria, Iraq, Nepal, Eritrea,

01:06:52.408 --> 01:06:53.343 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
the Ivory Coast, Guinea-Conakry. They re all
working each on their own dish and we have

01:06:53.443 --> 01:06:55.245 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
a few deliveries happening this afternoon.

01:06:55.345 --> 01:06:57.146 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
BRANGHAM: Manal Kahi created Eat Offbeat with
her brother Wissam last year. The idea came

01:06:57.247 --> 01:06:58.381 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
to them a few years before, after Kahi kept
trying different brands of American made hummus

01:06:58.481 --> 01:07:00.250 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
and nothing measured up to her grandmother s
recipe.

01:07:00.350 --> 01:07:02.085 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
KAHI: I had recently moved to the U.S. from
Lebanon and I kind of missed my home. In the

01:07:02.185 --> 01:07:03.887 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
midst of the refugee crisis back in Lebanon,
our grandmother happens to be from Aleppo,

01:07:03.987 --> 01:07:05.889 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
from Syria, originally. It was relatively
natural for us to say if you want someone

01:07:05.989 --> 01:07:07.457 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
as talented as our grandmother to make hummus
for New Yorkers, maybe we should see the refugees

01:07:07.557 --> 01:07:09.292 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
coming from Syria. We probably would findsomeone who s just like her.

01:07:09.392 --> 01:07:11.194 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
BRANGHAM: That idea soon grew beyond just
Syrians -- Kahi believed that talented home

01:07:11.294 --> 01:07:11.628 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
cooks from across the globe could offer New
Yorkers unique flavors, prepared in traditional

01:07:11.728 --> 01:07:13.529 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
ways.

01:07:13.630 --> 01:07:15.365 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
KAHI: Cuisines like Iraqi food, Syrian, Nepali,
Eritrean, it s not really cuisines that you

01:07:15.465 --> 01:07:17.166 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
can find around every corner even here in
New York, as cosmopolitan as it can be. When

01:07:17.267 --> 01:07:19.002 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
we say authentic, it s not necessarily the
way it s made in that country or it s been

01:07:19.102 --> 01:07:20.403 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
made in that country hundred years ago. It s
the way they make it at home, the way they

01:07:20.503 --> 01:07:22.405 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
eat it with their families. That s the way
we re selling it.

01:07:22.505 --> 01:07:23.573 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
BRANGHAM: Eat Offbeat partners with the International
Rescue Committee to find their chefs, and

01:07:23.673 --> 01:07:25.508 align:left position:62.5%,start line:93.33% size:37.5%
twelve of them are now employed with the company.

01:07:25.608 --> 01:07:27.343 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Because it s their first time working in a
professional kitchen, they need a bit of training,

01:07:27.443 --> 01:07:28.678 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
and so, the culinary process is overseen by
head chef Juan Suarez De Lezo. He s worked

01:07:28.778 --> 01:07:30.546 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
at some of the top restaurants in both Spain
and the U.S.

01:07:30.647 --> 01:07:32.382 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
JUAN SUAREZ DE LEZO, HEAD CHEF: I m teaching
them how to move in a professional kitchen,

01:07:32.482 --> 01:07:34.250 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
how to work, how to organize, how to balance
flavors, because at the end, they ve been

01:07:34.350 --> 01:07:35.919 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
cooking always for their families which is
amazing, but in this case, now they re cooking

01:07:36.019 --> 01:07:37.854 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
for New Yorkers. So, they need to adapt thoseflavors in somehow for the city.

01:07:37.954 --> 01:07:38.922 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
BRANGHAM: For Rachana Rimal, a Nepalese chef,
she s been preparing a dish that is generally

01:07:39.022 --> 01:07:40.456 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
served at special occasions in her country.

01:07:40.556 --> 01:07:41.224 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
RACHANA RIMAL, CHIEF, EAT OFFBEAT: This isa chicken ball, actually.

01:07:41.324 --> 01:07:43.059 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
BRANGHAM: Like a meatball?

01:07:43.159 --> 01:07:44.127 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
RIMAL: Like a meatball but I put a lot of
spices on it, like onions and my ingredients

01:07:44.227 --> 01:07:45.995 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
here, culmi, mustard. I put everything here.

01:07:46.095 --> 01:07:47.864 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
BRANGHAM: Rimal s daughter Satakshi came to
the U.S. with her a few years ago when they

01:07:47.964 --> 01:07:49.732 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
fled Nepal as a family. She works as the kitchen
manager for Eat Offbeat. With a meticulous

01:07:49.832 --> 01:07:50.400 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
eye, she oversees deliveries, portion sizes,
and, for the first time in her life, keeping

01:07:50.500 --> 01:07:52.268 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
her own mom in line.

01:07:52.368 --> 01:07:53.870 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
SATAKSHI RIMAL, KITCHEN MANAGER, EAT OFFBEAT:
I get to boss her around here and she gets

01:07:53.970 --> 01:07:55.705 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
to boss me around at home. So, I think weeven each other out pretty well.

01:07:55.805 --> 01:07:57.507 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
BRANGHAM: Larry Younck is a senior refugee
resettlement officer for the United Nations

01:07:57.607 --> 01:07:58.408 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
in Washington, D.C. Younck says cooking is
often a perfect job for refugees when they

01:07:58.508 --> 01:08:00.276 align:left position:87.5%,start line:93.33% size:12.5%
first arrive to the United States.

01:08:00.376 --> 01:08:02.111 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
LARRY YOUNCK, SENIOR REFUGEE RESETTLEMENT
OFFICER, UNITED NATIONS: Refugees are expected

01:08:02.211 --> 01:08:03.980 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
to be self-supporting very quickly, a few
months after arriving here, and to find jobs

01:08:04.080 --> 01:08:05.815 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
in the U.S. and that can be a challenge when
you don t speak English or you speak limited

01:08:05.915 --> 01:08:07.617 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
English and your job skills maybe are hard
to transfer from your home country. But when

01:08:07.717 --> 01:08:09.552 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
it comes to food, food communicates regardless
of whether you can speak English or not.

01:08:09.652 --> 01:08:10.219 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
BRANGHAM: Younck also believes more companies
should follow Eat Offbeat s lead when it comes

01:08:10.320 --> 01:08:12.221 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to hiring refugees.

01:08:12.322 --> 01:08:14.057 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
YOUNCK: What we see is refugees in general
in a lot of walks of life are much more entrepreneurial

01:08:14.157 --> 01:08:15.391 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
than typically Americans are because, again,
they ve taken risks. They know what it is

01:08:15.491 --> 01:08:17.193 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
to try something and maybe you succeed and
maybe you don t.

01:08:17.293 --> 01:08:18.928 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
BRANGHAM: But Manal Kahi wants her company
to go further, not just to offer jobs, but

01:08:19.028 --> 01:08:20.763 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
to help change the perception of refugees
as just being vulnerable, needy people.

01:08:20.863 --> 01:08:22.598 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
KAHI: That s exactly what they re trying to
prove wrong. In our opinion, refugees are

01:08:22.699 --> 01:08:24.467 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
very skilled. They bring with them a lot of
skills, a lot of talent, a lot of heritage

01:08:24.567 --> 01:08:26.369 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
that they can share with their host communities.
And given the right opportunity, the right

01:08:26.469 --> 01:08:28.237 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
space, they have a lot to contribute for the
local economy, and for the local communities.

01:08:28.338 --> 01:08:29.272 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
BRANGHAM: And for employees like Satakshi
Rimal, she says the kitchen has become a place

01:08:29.372 --> 01:08:31.107 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
where chefs do much more than simply cook.

01:08:31.207 --> 01:08:33.009 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
RIMAL: The best I could describe is it s a
second home to everybody. It s like a bunch

01:08:33.109 --> 01:08:34.877 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
of aunts coming in, cooking at a common kitchen.
And, you know, it s like joint family so you

01:08:34.978 --> 01:08:36.512 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
have everything that happens in a household.
There s screaming, there s, "hey, don t put

01:08:36.612 --> 01:08:38.414 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
too much of this. Don t put so much of it."Even if that s not their dish.

01:08:38.514 --> 01:08:40.316 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
BRANGHAM: Eat Offbeat mainly caters to large
groups, but is hoping to expand into a delivery

01:08:40.416 --> 01:08:40.984 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
service in the coming months. And as for the
hummus -- Kahi says her company s recipe would

01:08:41.084 --> 01:08:41.651 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
make grandma proud.

01:08:41.751 --> 01:08:42.986 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Mmm, that is great.

01:08:43.086 --> 01:08:43.553 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
For the "PBS NewsHour", I m William Brangham
in New York.

